{
  "text": "While future studies are necessary to establish whether these and other areas are critical for seizure initiation, published data provide some clues. The parasubiculum receives major inputs from glutamatergic cells of the CA1 and cholinergic cells of the medial septum as well as minor inputs from the subiculum, anterior thalamus and basolateral amygdala. The main efferents project to layer II of the entorhinal cortex, which in turn projects to the dentate granule cells and CA3 pyramidal neurons as the perforant pathway Witter, 1993, 1994; [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Furthermore, presubicular neurons can generate theta frequency EEG activity, probably via membrane potential oscillations that are synchronized by local inhibitory inputs [CITATION_4] . Theta activity is important for modulation of hippocampal cognitive function, emotional behavior, stress and anxietymodalities that are often affected in MTLE [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Hippocampal theta activity is also altered in human MTLE [CITATION_7] and in relevant animal models of the disease [CITATION_8] . Finally, neurons in layers II and III of the parasubiculum, including parvalbumin-positive cells, are lost in animal models of MTLE, suggesting that local network changes involving the parasubiculum occur in epilepsy [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . The significance of the entorhinal cortex and amygdala for MTLE has already been discussed.",
  "correct_citation": {
